JOINS
************************************************************************************************
JOINS : joins are used to combain the data from two or more tables by using column names

1. INNER JOIN: returns only matching rows from both tables
 
  Syntax  : SELECT columns FROM table 1 INNER JOIN table 2 ON table1.column = table2.column;

  Example : SELECT w.id, w.name, d.dept_name FROM workers w INNER JOIN department d ON w.dept_id = d.dept_id;

Filter the Condition :
 
    SELECT columns FROM table1 INNER JOIN table2 ON table1.column = table2.column WHERE d.dept_name = 'dept-name';

2. LEFT JOIN : Returns all records from the left table and matching records from the right table. Non-matching rows show NULL.

  Syntax : SELECT coloumns FROM table 1 LEFT JOIN table 2 ON table1.column = table2.column;
   
  Example : SELECT w.id, w.name, d.dept_name FROM workers w LEFT JOIN department d ON W.dept_id = d.dept_id;


3. RIGHT JOIN : Right join returns all joins from the right table and matching rows from the left table. if there is no match the left table column contains will NULL.

 Syntax : SELECT column_name FROM left_table RIGHT right_table ON left_table.column_name = right_table.column_name;

 Example : SELECT w.id, w.name, d.dept_name FROM workers w RIGHT JOIN department d ON w.dept_id = d.dept_id;

4.SELF JOIN : A SELF JOIN is a join in which a table is joined with itself. It is commonly used to represent hierarchical relationships such as Employee–Manager.

Syntax : SELECT a.column1, b.column2 FROM table_name a JOIN table_name b ON a.comman_column = b.comman_column;

Example : SELECT e.emp_name AS Employee, m.emp_name AS Manager FROM employee_manager e LEFT JOIN employee_manager m ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;


